text: I have this really cool idea for a sequel ( I saw this one, it was epic ). The main villains would be Daken ( Wolverine's son ), and Domino. It would be about them being hired by Weapon X to take down Deadpool to use his DNA for forced mutations. Their intention is actually to perfect his mutational  abilities and blend them with other powerful mutant DNA so they could create their army of super mutant soldiers. When Daken and Domino repeatedly fail to recover Deadpool's DNA, Weapon X dispatches their most powerful mutants by placing a bounty on Deadpool's head. It attracts the attention of villains such as Omega Red, Sabretooth and Lady Deathstrike. Deadpool escapes to New York where he causes massive destruction. It attracts the atention of the Punisher. At first, he is also involved with taking out Deadpool because he thinks he is a bad guy but later he becomes his companion. Tell me what do you think about it, I just thought it would be a cool idea.

text: 1:06 - That's Marrow!!! Not at all one of my favorite X-Men from one of the eras in comics I not-so-affectionately refer to as The Beginning Of The End (Of well written comics that is) but... That's Marrow!!! I still get a bit goosepimply when I see characters I grew up with portrayed visually well on the "Silver Screen"! It causes me to use (!)'s in my comments when I normally wouldn't. I say visually well because from what little we see here I can tell they will do their usual damage in making changes to a character that is totally unnecessary and invariably diminishes the character. I still don't understand why the don't just stick with the script (the original comics) when the popularity of those comics is the reason why they are able to obtain funding for the movies in the first place. Besides, how much money could they save in script writing fees to say nothing of the fact that they have a surefire winner if they simply commit to film what sold so well on the 4 colored page?

text: I'm definitely in the minority here. The movie was well made, but the writing needed to be much much stronger and more intelligent. And Deadpool needed to mock movie conventions as opposed to falling write in to them. It needed more puns, many more jokes, more 4th wall breaks, and it had to be wackier. Also where were the speech bubbles? The story was pretty generic at the end of the day and the movie also got a bit too serious for it's own good. There was such a good platform for the perfect Deadpool movie which wasn't exploited imo. But it's good that the studio actually allowed an R rated antihero movie to be made, and that it's doing so well.

text: you know i've learned alotta life lessons watching the movies i like. From THE LAST SAMURAI, i learned i had to power to forget and erase the past [no matter how tragic] while embracing the present to make room for the future. THE MATRIX showed me the power of PURPOSE and how important it is to know WHY you're here. MAN OF STEEL taught me to embrace destiny while understanding the journey of identity..... of course in BATMAN BEGINS, which is my fave superhero BTW, i learned the greatest line from Liam Neeson- " The training is NOTHING; but the WILL is EVERYTHING! THE WILL TO ACT!"  and now the latest thing i learned from watching DEADPOOL is my new maxim=MAXIMUM EFFORT! trust me folks, this stuff is real and it works for me in makin life smoother! we should put maximum effort in what we do; however it still requires strong will to act on that impulse! hence what made DEADPOOl slice up bad guys so good!

text: simply the most literate ( for deadpool anyway), funny, faithful, and energetic comic book movie in years. The Avengers, Winter Soldier, and Iron Man are the best as far as Marvel Studios goes. But for the X-men universe this film is tops. It is so similar to the first Iron Man in the sense that it tells a very simple story with a very tight run time. Ryan Reynolds will never be confused for Laurence Olivier but his performance just screams energy and total commitment ( and fan familiarity) to the role. Movies this gory ( like Blade) are usually mean spirited and ugly. Deadpool is so self aware and fun that all the violence is not completely off putting. I know they will be making sequels but I wish they just leave it all alone. It will never capture lightening in a bottle like this again. It can't because now we're in on the joke. It may seem like hyperbole but for me, this is already on my top ten list for 2016. Proof that you can make a great action film for a small budget( when did 50 million mean small budget!?). The movie does it right. Cast a likable " name" leading man,  competent but little know supporting actors, limited but solid CGI, and a ton of energy ( I know I'm repeating myself) and number one: respect and reverence for the character and fans.

text: I've been thinking of watching Deadpool, but I'm not sure. I know it's R rated and everyone says that it was beyond awesome. However, I can't mentally or physically handle the cursing and "revealing" scenes. To most people it's no big deal and they tell me to grow up or that I'm being immature. I'm not religious; I do believe in a god, but that has nothing to do with why it effects me in that way. I feel nauseous when I talk or think about coitus and seeing anyone (even babies) naked grosses me out to the point of vomiting. When I hear curse words it feels like I'm being stabbed or punched in the chest. I love the Deadpool charater and I've been waiting for a movie about him since I found out about him in the ultimate spider man series. I really want to see it. Hopefully, I can get through more than 5 minutes of the movie. I believe I know why it effects me in that way.   And it's not something I can just get over because someone tells me to.
